// Semantic direction:
// sql_engine parses SQL text, plans the query, and executes it against relations.
// sql_ast represents the parsed query tree; sql_plan is the physical execution plan.
// relation is a named set of typed rows; tuple_row is one record.
// select_stmt implements the core SELECT projection, filtering, grouping, and ordering.
// select_distinct removes duplicate rows from the result using hash-based deduplication.
// expr_case_when evaluates conditional expressions: CASE WHEN condition THEN value END.
// expr_in_list checks if a value matches any element in a literal or subquery list.
// expr_exists returns true if a correlated subquery produces any row.
// relational_algebra provides the physical operators that implement SQL semantics.
// ra_scan reads all rows from a relation; ra_filter applies a predicate row by row.
// ra_project discards columns not needed by the query.
// ra_hash_join builds a hash table from the build side and probes with the probe side.
// ra_merge_join requires both inputs sorted on the join key; it merges them in one pass.
// ra_aggregate groups rows by key and applies aggregate functions (sum, count, avg).
// ra_sort orders rows by the sort key using an external merge sort for large datasets.
// query_planner transforms a logical_plan into an optimized physical_plan.
// rule_push_filter moves filter conditions as close to the scan as possible.
// rule_join_reorder selects the join order that minimizes the estimated intermediate size.
// rule_use_index replaces a full_table_scan with an index_scan when a matching index exists.
// statistics records cardinality and value distribution per column for cost estimation.
// cost_model estimates the compute and I/O cost of each plan_node for plan selection.
// batch_iterator yields rows in vectorized batches for CPU cache efficiency.

// Primitive flow:
// sql_parse("SELECT ...") -> sql_ast
// query_planner: sql_ast -> logical_plan -> optimize -> physical_plan
//   rule_push_filter: move WHERE below JOIN
//   rule_use_index: replace scan with index_seek if predicate matches index
//   rule_join_reorder: smallest estimated_rows as build_side
// execute: physical_plan -> pipeline_execute
//   ra_scan -> ra_filter -> ra_hash_join -> ra_aggregate -> ra_sort -> ra_limit_op
//   -> row_iterator -> sql_result rows

// This defines the SQL query engine: parser, relational algebra operators,
// cost-based query planner, and vectorized execution pipeline.
